            <div type="general">
               <head>General</head>
               <p xml:space="preserve">The Siwa Oasis is located in the Libyan desert and is mostly inhabited by Amazighis, which 
                   according to sources from al-Idrīsī was already the case in the 12th century. Siwa is also 
                   the easternmost region where an Amazight language is spoken.</p>
               <p xml:space="preserve">Today most residents- especially the younger generations- are bilinguals. As Arabic is the 
                   language of the authorities and education, Siwi became an endangered language.</p>
                
            </div>
            <div type="researchHistory">
               <head>Research history</head>
               <p><rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:BP7M6678">Souag (2009)</rs> points to the importance of Siwi for Arabic dialectology arguing that the analysis of its Arabic 
                   elements provides information on the history of Arabic in the region.</p>
               <p><rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:9XSMFXLS">Serreli (2018)</rs> focuses on the sociolinguistic situation in Siwa. Although the article talks mainly about the 
                   Berber language Siwi it draws a picture of the co-existence with Arabic in the Oasis of Siwa.</p>
            </div>

            

